The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Chennai, Jan. 17 (PTI): A senior Indian Space Research Organisation official and his wife were killed in a car accident in Chennai today.           
	Isro group director Krishna Rao, 55, and his wife Susheela, 50, were returning to Sulurpet from Chennai after seeing off their son, who went abroad. The driver lost control and rammed into a parked lorry from behind. The driver sustained multiple fractures, police said.                   
	 Ahmedabad (PTI): A group of five to seven lions killed a 28-year-old man in a village near Gir reserved forest in Gujarat on Saturday. Rajesh Parmar and three of his friends were attacked while they were walking through the forest.                  
	 Washington (PTI): An African American has been charged with triple murder, including that of Akshay Vishal, the Satyam techie from Hyderabad who was killed in Little Rocks on Tuesday. Brandon Johnson, 20, has been allegedly involved in about a dozen robberies and was arrested on Thursday. His girlfriend Victoria McCoy has been arrested for using Vishals credit card.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Aamir Khan has recorded his statement as a witness in a road accident case where an 83-year-old was fatally knocked down, allegedly by a minor driver. Aamir has not committed himself to testifying in the trial, deputy commissioner of police Niket Kaushik said.                   
	 Islamabad (PTI): Thirty-six Indians are among 141 foreigners still lodged in Pakistani jails despite having completed their prison terms, interior ministry officials said. These inmates were lodged in Lahore, Rawalpindi and Peshawar jails and could not be released because they did not have travel documents, they said.                   
	 Pathanamthitta, Kerala (PTI): Twenty Sri Lankan Tamil pilgrims visiting the shrine in Sabarimala have been arrested since they did not possess proper travel documents.
                                                                                                                           
